As the proposed model is able to describe the transition from an exponential to a power-law epidemic growth, and is capable to provide meaningful predictions on the epidemic trend using only few parameters, it is important to validate it with real data. Therefore, we next tested the model against data from the first and second waves of COVID-19 in Italy. The epidemiological data are very sensitive to the ability of a given country in testing the population, identifying new cases among asymptomatic people, which reflects the capacity of the health system2. During the first wave, testing was restricted by lack of reagents, so the number of positive individuals has been largely underestimated. Daily data for the second wave are much more reliable, thanks to more extensive testing. For this reason, we look at the time evolution of different indexes that are (i) Daily new positive cases (NP), (ii) Positive cases at a given time (P), (iii) Hospitalized cases (H), and (iv) Daily deaths (D). The latter two indicators are independent of testing capacity. The fitting parameters are the mobility parameter \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
